01063 /**
01064  * cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfg#
01065  *
01066  * Notes:
01067  * The actual SKIP I determined by HW is based on the packet contents.  BIT0 and
01068  * BIT1 make up a two value value that the selects the skip value as follows.
01069  *
01070  *    lookup_value = LEN ? ( packet_in_bits[BIT1], packet_in_bits[BIT0] ) : ( 0, packet_in_bits[BIT0] );
01071  *    SKIP I       = lookup_value == 3 ? SKIP3 :
01072  *                   lookup_value == 2 ? SKIP2 :
01073  *                   lookup_value == 1 ? SKIP1 :
01074  *                   PIP_PRT_CFG<pknd>[SKIP];
01075  */
01076 union cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx {
01077     uint64_t u64;
01078     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s {
01079 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01080     uint64_t reserved_57_63               : 7;
01081     uint64_t len                          : 1;  /**< Indicates the length of the selection field
01082                                                          0 = 0,    BIT0
01083                                                          1 = BIT1, BIT0 */
01084     uint64_t reserved_46_55               : 10;
01085     uint64_t bit1                         : 6;  /**< Indicates the bit location in the first word of
01086                                                          the packet to use to select the skip amount.
01087                                                          BIT1 must be present in the packet. */
01088     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
01089     uint64_t bit0                         : 6;  /**< Indicates the bit location in the first word of
01090                                                          the packet to use to select the skip amount.
01091                                                          BIT0 must be present in the packet. */
01092     uint64_t reserved_23_31               : 9;
01093     uint64_t skip3                        : 7;  /**< Indicates number of bytes to skip from start of
01094                                                          packet 0-64 */
01095     uint64_t reserved_15_15               : 1;
01096     uint64_t skip2                        : 7;  /**< Indicates number of bytes to skip from start of
01097                                                          packet 0-64 */
01098     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
01099     uint64_t skip1                        : 7;  /**< Indicates number of bytes to skip from start of
01100                                                          packet 0-64 */
01101 #else
01102     uint64_t skip1                        : 7;
01103     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
01104     uint64_t skip2                        : 7;
01105     uint64_t reserved_15_15               : 1;
01106     uint64_t skip3                        : 7;
01107     uint64_t reserved_23_31               : 9;
01108     uint64_t bit0                         : 6;
01109     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
01110     uint64_t bit1                         : 6;
01111     uint64_t reserved_46_55               : 10;
01112     uint64_t len                          : 1;
01113     uint64_t reserved_57_63               : 7;
01114 #endif
01115     } s;
01116     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s       cn61xx;
01117     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s       cn66xx;
01118     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s       cn68xx;
01119     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s       cn70xx;
01120     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s       cn70xxp1;
01121     struct cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_s       cnf71xx;
01122 };
01123 typedef union cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx cvmx_pip_alt_skip_cfgx_t;

01125 /**
01126  * cvmx_pip_bck_prs
01127  *
01128  * When to assert backpressure based on the todo list filling up
01129  *
01130  */
01131 union cvmx_pip_bck_prs {
01132     uint64_t u64;
01133     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s {
01134 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01135     uint64_t bckprs                       : 1;  /**< PIP is currently asserting backpressure to IOB
01136                                                          Backpressure from PIP will assert when the
01137                                                          entries to the todo list exceed HIWATER.
01138                                                          Backpressure will be held until the todo entries
01139                                                          is less than or equal to LOWATER. */
01140     uint64_t reserved_13_62               : 50;
01141     uint64_t hiwater                      : 5;  /**< Water mark in the todo list to assert backpressure
01142                                                          Legal values are 1-26.  A 0 value will deadlock
01143                                                          the machine.  A value > 26, will trash memory */
01144     uint64_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
01145     uint64_t lowater                      : 5;  /**< Water mark in the todo list to release backpressure
01146                                                          The LOWATER value should be < HIWATER. */
01147 #else
01148     uint64_t lowater                      : 5;
01149     uint64_t reserved_5_7                 : 3;
01150     uint64_t hiwater                      : 5;
01151     uint64_t reserved_13_62               : 50;
01152     uint64_t bckprs                       : 1;
01153 #endif
01154     } s;
01155     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn38xx;
01156     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn38xxp2;
01157     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn56xx;
01158     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn56xxp1;
01159     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn58xx;
01160     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn58xxp1;
01161     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn61xx;
01162     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn63xx;
01163     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn63xxp1;
01164     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn66xx;
01165     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn68xx;
01166     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn68xxp1;
01167     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn70xx;
01168     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cn70xxp1;
01169     struct cvmx_pip_bck_prs_s             cnf71xx;
01170 };
01171 typedef union cvmx_pip_bck_prs cvmx_pip_bck_prs_t;

01173 /**

01175  *
01176  * PIP_BIST_STATUS = PIP's BIST Results
01177  *
01178  */
01179 union cvmx_pip_bist_status {
01180     uint64_t u64;
01181     struct cvmx_pip_bist_status_s {
01182 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01183     uint64_t reserved_22_63               : 42;
01184     uint64_t bist                         : 22; /**< BIST Results.
01185                                                          HW sets a bit in BIST for for memory that fails
01186                                                          BIST. */
01187 #else
01188     uint64_t bist                         : 22;
01189     uint64_t reserved_22_63               : 42;
01190 #endif
01191     } s;
01192     struct cvmx_pip_bist_status_cn30xx {

01485 /**
01486  * cvmx_pip_crc_iv#
01487  *
01488  * PIP_CRC_IV = PIP CRC IV Register
01489  *
01490  * Determines the IV used by the CRC algorithm
01491  *
01492  * Notes:
01493  * * PIP_CRC_IV
01494  * PIP_CRC_IV controls the initial state of the CRC algorithm.  Octane can
01495  * support a wide range of CRC algorithms and as such, the IV must be
01496  * carefully constructed to meet the specific algorithm.  The code below
01497  * determines the value to program into Octane based on the algorthim's IV
01498  * and width.  In the case of Octane, the width should always be 32.
01499  *
01500  * PIP_CRC_IV0 sets the IV for ports 0-15 while PIP_CRC_IV1 sets the IV for
01501  * ports 16-31.
01502  *
01503  *  unsigned octane_crc_iv(unsigned algorithm_iv, unsigned poly, unsigned w)
01504  *  [
01505  *    int i;
01506  *    int doit;
01507  *    unsigned int current_val = algorithm_iv;
01508  *
01509  *    for(i = 0; i < w; i++) [
01510  *      doit = current_val & 0x1;
01511  *
01512  *      if(doit) current_val ^= poly;
01513  *      assert(!(current_val & 0x1));
01514  *
01515  *      current_val = (current_val >> 1) | (doit << (w-1));
01516  *    ]
01517  *
01518  *    return current_val;
01519  *  ]
01520  */
01521 union cvmx_pip_crc_ivx {
01522     uint64_t u64;
01523     struct cvmx_pip_crc_ivx_s {
01524 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01525     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
01526     uint64_t iv                           : 32; /**< IV used by the CRC algorithm.  Default is FCS32. */
01527 #else
01528     uint64_t iv                           : 32;
01529     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
01530 #endif
01531     } s;
01532     struct cvmx_pip_crc_ivx_s             cn38xx;
01533     struct cvmx_pip_crc_ivx_s             cn38xxp2;
01534     struct cvmx_pip_crc_ivx_s             cn58xx;
01535     struct cvmx_pip_crc_ivx_s             cn58xxp1;
01536 };
01537 typedef union cvmx_pip_crc_ivx cvmx_pip_crc_ivx_t;
01538

01699 /**
01700  * cvmx_pip_frm_len_chk#
01701  *
01702  * Notes:
01703  * PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK0 is used for packets on packet interface0, PCI, PCI RAW, and PKO loopback ports.
01704  * PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK1 is unused.
01705  */
01706 union cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx {
01707     uint64_t u64;
01708     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s {
01709 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
01710     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
01711     uint64_t maxlen                       : 16; /**< Byte count for Max-sized frame check
01712                                                          PIP_PRT_CFGn[MAXERR_EN] enables the check for
01713                                                          port n.
01714                                                          If enabled, failing packets set the MAXERR
01715                                                          interrupt and work-queue entry WORD2[opcode] is
01716                                                          set to OVER_FCS (0x3, if packet has bad FCS) or
01717                                                          OVER_ERR (0x4, if packet has good FCS).
01718                                                          The effective MAXLEN used by HW is
01719                                                          PIP_PRT_CFG[DSA_EN] == 0,
01720                                                           PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK[MAXLEN] + 4*VV + 4*VS
01721                                                          PIP_PRT_CFG[DSA_EN] == 1,
01722                                                           PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK[MAXLEN] + PIP_PRT_CFG[SKIP]+4*VS
01723                                                          If PTP_MODE, the 8B timestamp is prepended to the
01724                                                           packet.  MAXLEN should be increased by 8 to
01725                                                           compensate for the additional timestamp field. */
01726     uint64_t minlen                       : 16; /**< Byte count for Min-sized frame check
01727                                                          PIP_PRT_CFGn[MINERR_EN] enables the check for
01728                                                          port n.
01729                                                          If enabled, failing packets set the MINERR
01730                                                          interrupt and work-queue entry WORD2[opcode] is
01731                                                          set to UNDER_FCS (0x6, if packet has bad FCS) or
01732                                                          UNDER_ERR (0x8, if packet has good FCS).
01733                                                          If PTP_MODE, the 8B timestamp is prepended to the
01734                                                           packet.  MINLEN should be increased by 8 to
01735                                                           compensate for the additional timestamp field. */
01736 #else
01737     uint64_t minlen                       : 16;
01738     uint64_t maxlen                       : 16;
01739     uint64_t reserved_32_63               : 32;
01740 #endif
01741     } s;
01742     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s        cn50xx;
01743     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s        cn52xx;
01744     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s        cn52xxp1;
01745     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s        cn56xx;
01746     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s        cn56xxp1;
01747     struct cvmx_pip_frm_len_chkx_s        cn61xx;

02277 /**
02278  * cvmx_pip_hg_pri_qos
02279  *
02280  * Notes:
02281  * This register controls accesses to the HG_QOS_TABLE.  To write an entry of
02282  * the table, write PIP_HG_PRI_QOS with PRI=table address, QOS=priority level,
02283  * UP_QOS=1.  To read an entry of the table, write PIP_HG_PRI_QOS with
02284  * PRI=table address, QOS=dont_carepriority level, UP_QOS=0 and then read
02285  * PIP_HG_PRI_QOS.  The table data will be in PIP_HG_PRI_QOS[QOS].
02286  */

02288     uint64_t u64;
02289     struct cvmx_pip_hg_pri_qos_s {

02293                                                          HG_QOS_TABLE as specified by PRI to a value of
02294                                                          QOS as follows
02295                                                          HG_QOS_TABLE[PRI] = QOS */
02296     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
02297     uint64_t qos                          : 3;  /**< QOS Map level to priority */
02298     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
02299     uint64_t pri                          : 6;  /**< The priority level from HiGig header
02300                                                          HiGig/HiGig+ PRI = [1'b0, CNG[1:0], COS[2:0]]
02301                                                          HiGig2       PRI = [DP[1:0], TC[3:0]] */
02302 #else
02303     uint64_t pri                          : 6;
02304     uint64_t reserved_6_7                 : 2;
02305     uint64_t qos                          : 3;
02306     uint64_t reserved_11_11               : 1;
02307     uint64_t up_qos                       : 1;
02308     uint64_t reserved_13_63               : 51;
02309 #endif
02310     } s;

02789                                                          - 2: 16 Bytes / IP start at WORD6 of workQ entry
02790                                                          - 3: 24 Bytes / IP start at WORD7 of workQ entry
02791                                                          - 4: 32 Bytes / IP start at WORD8 of workQ entry
02792                                                          - 5: 40 Bytes / IP start at WORD9 of workQ entry
02793                                                          - 6: 48 Bytes / IP start at WORD10 of workQ entry

02823 /**
02824  * cvmx_pip_pri_tbl#
02825  *
02826  * Notes:
02827  * The priority level from HiGig header is as follows
02828  *
02829  * HiGig/HiGig+ PRI = [1'b0, CNG[1:0], COS[2:0]]
02830  * HiGig2       PRI = [DP[1:0], TC[3:0]]
02831  *
02832  * DSA          PRI = WORD0[15:13]
02833  *
02834  * VLAN         PRI = VLAN[15:13]
02835  *
02836  * DIFFSERV         = IP.TOS/CLASS<7:2>
02837  */
02838 union cvmx_pip_pri_tblx {
02839     uint64_t u64;
02840     struct cvmx_pip_pri_tblx_s {
02841 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
02842     uint64_t diff2_padd                   : 8;  /**< Diffserv port-add */
02843     uint64_t hg2_padd                     : 8;  /**< HG_PRI port-add */
02844     uint64_t vlan2_padd                   : 8;  /**< VLAN port-add */
02845     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
02846     uint64_t diff2_bpid                   : 6;  /**< Diffserv backpressure ID */
02847     uint64_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
02848     uint64_t hg2_bpid                     : 6;  /**< HG_PRI backpressure ID */
02849     uint64_t reserved_22_23               : 2;
02850     uint64_t vlan2_bpid                   : 6;  /**< VLAN backpressure ID */
02851     uint64_t reserved_11_15               : 5;
02852     uint64_t diff2_qos                    : 3;  /**< Diffserv QOS level */
02853     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
02854     uint64_t hg2_qos                      : 3;  /**< HG_PRI QOS level */
02855     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
02856     uint64_t vlan2_qos                    : 3;  /**< VLAN QOS level */
02857 #else
02858     uint64_t vlan2_qos                    : 3;
02859     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
02860     uint64_t hg2_qos                      : 3;
02861     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
02862     uint64_t diff2_qos                    : 3;
02863     uint64_t reserved_11_15               : 5;
02864     uint64_t vlan2_bpid                   : 6;
02865     uint64_t reserved_22_23               : 2;
02866     uint64_t hg2_bpid                     : 6;
02867     uint64_t reserved_30_31               : 2;
02868     uint64_t diff2_bpid                   : 6;
02869     uint64_t reserved_38_39               : 2;
02870     uint64_t vlan2_padd                   : 8;
02871     uint64_t hg2_padd                     : 8;
02872     uint64_t diff2_padd                   : 8;
02873 #endif
02874     } s;
02875     struct cvmx_pip_pri_tblx_s            cn68xx;

02889 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

02891     uint64_t ih_pri                       : 1;  /**< Use the PRI/QOS field in the instruction header
02892                                                          as the PRIORITY in BPID calculations. */
02893     uint64_t len_chk_sel                  : 1;  /**< Selects which PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK register is used
02894                                                          for this port-kind for MINERR and MAXERR checks.
02895                                                          LEN_CHK_SEL=0, use PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK0
02896                                                          LEN_CHK_SEL=1, use PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK1 */
02897     uint64_t pad_len                      : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for pkts with
02898                                                          padding in the client data */
02899     uint64_t vlan_len                     : 1;  /**< When set, disables the length check for DSA/VLAN
02900                                                          pkts */
02901     uint64_t lenerr_en                    : 1;  /**< L2 length error check enable
02902                                                          Frame was received with length error
02903                                                           Typically, this check will not be enabled for
02904                                                           incoming packets on the DPI and sRIO ports
02905                                                           because the CRC bytes may not normally be
02906                                                           present. */
02907     uint64_t maxerr_en                    : 1;  /**< Max frame error check enable
02908                                                          Frame was received with length > max_length
02909                                                          max_length is defined by PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK[MAXLEN] */
02910     uint64_t minerr_en                    : 1;  /**< Min frame error check enable
02911                                                          Frame was received with length < min_length
02912                                                           Typically, this check will not be enabled for
02913                                                           incoming packets on the DPI and sRIO ports
02914                                                           because the CRC bytes may not normally be
02915                                                           present.
02916                                                           min_length is defined by PIP_FRM_LEN_CHK[MINLEN] */
02917     uint64_t grp_wat_47                   : 4;  /**< GRP Watcher enable
02918                                                          (Watchers 4-7) */
02919     uint64_t qos_wat_47                   : 4;  /**< QOS Watcher enable
02920                                                          (Watchers 4-7) */
02921     uint64_t reserved_37_39               : 3;
02922     uint64_t rawdrp                       : 1;  /**< Allow the IPD to RED drop a packet.
02923                                                          Normally, IPD will never drop a packet that PIP
02924                                                          indicates is RAW.
02925                                                          0=never drop RAW packets based on RED algorithm
02926                                                          1=allow RAW packet drops based on RED algorithm */
02927     uint64_t tag_inc                      : 2;  /**< Which of the 4 PIP_TAG_INC to use when
02928                                                          calculating mask tag hash */
02929     uint64_t dyn_rs                       : 1;  /**< Dynamically calculate RS based on pkt size and
02930                                                          configuration.  If DYN_RS is set then
02931                                                          PKT_INST_HDR[RS] is not used.  When using 2-byte
02932                                                          instruction header words, either DYN_RS or
02933                                                          PIP_GBL_CTL[IGNRS] should be set. */
02934     uint64_t inst_hdr                     : 1;  /**< 8-byte INST_HDR is present on all packets
02935                                                          Internally set for RAWFULL/RAWSCHED packets
02936                                                          on the DPI ports (32-35).
02937                                                          Internally cleared for all other packets on the
02938                                                          DPI ports (32-35).
02939                                                          Must be zero in DSA mode */
02940     uint64_t grp_wat                      : 4;  /**< GRP Watcher enable */
02941     uint64_t hg_qos                       : 1;  /**< When set, uses the HiGig priority bits as a
02942                                                          lookup into the HG_QOS_TABLE (PIP_HG_PRI_QOS)
02943                                                          to determine the QOS value
02944                                                          HG_QOS must not be set when HIGIG_EN=0 */
02945     uint64_t qos                          : 3;  /**< Default QOS level of the port */
02946     uint64_t qos_wat                      : 4;  /**< QOS Watcher enable
02947                                                          (Watchers 0-3) */
02948     uint64_t qos_vsel                     : 1;  /**< Which QOS in PIP_QOS_VLAN to use
02949                                                          0 = PIP_QOS_VLAN[QOS]
02950                                                          1 = PIP_QOS_VLAN[QOS1] */
02951     uint64_t qos_vod                      : 1;  /**< QOS VLAN over Diffserv
02952                                                          if DSA/VLAN exists, it is used
02953                                                          else if IP exists, Diffserv is used
02954                                                          else the per port default is used
02955                                                          Watchers are still highest priority */
02956     uint64_t qos_diff                     : 1;  /**< QOS Diffserv */
02957     uint64_t qos_vlan                     : 1;  /**< QOS VLAN */
02958     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
02959     uint64_t crc_en                       : 1;  /**< CRC Checking enabled */
02960     uint64_t higig_en                     : 1;  /**< Enable HiGig parsing
02961                                                          Should not be set for DPI ports (ports 32-35)
02962                                                          Should not be set for sRIO ports (ports 40-47)
02963                                                          Should not be set for ports in which PTP_MODE=1
02964                                                          When HIGIG_EN=1:
02965                                                           DSA_EN field below must be zero
02966                                                           PIP_PRT_CFGB[ALT_SKP_EN] must be zero.
02967                                                           SKIP field below is both Skip I size and the
02968                                                             size of the HiGig* header (12 or 16 bytes) */
02969     uint64_t dsa_en                       : 1;  /**< Enable DSA tag parsing
02970                                                          Should not be set for sRIO (ports 40-47)
02971                                                          Should not be set for ports in which PTP_MODE=1
02972                                                          When DSA_EN=1:
02973                                                           HIGIG_EN field above must be zero
02974                                                           SKIP field below is size of DSA tag (4, 8, or
02975                                                             12 bytes) rather than the size of Skip I
02976                                                           total SKIP (Skip I + header + Skip II
02977                                                             must be zero
02978                                                           INST_HDR field above must be zero (non-DPI
02979                                                             ports)
02980                                                           PIP_PRT_CFGB[ALT_SKP_EN] must be zero.
02981                                                           For DPI ports, SLI_PKT*_INSTR_HEADER[USE_IHDR]
02982                                                             and DPI_INST_HDR[R] should be clear
02983                                                           MODE field below must be "skip to L2" */
02984     cvmx_pip_port_parse_mode_t mode       : 2;  /**< Parse Mode
02985                                                          0 = no packet inspection (Uninterpreted)
02986                                                          1 = L2 parsing / skip to L2
02987                                                          2 = IP parsing / skip to L3
02988                                                          3 = (illegal)
02989                                                          Must be 2 ("skip to L2") when in DSA mode. */
02990     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
02991     uint64_t skip                         : 7;  /**< Optional Skip I amount for packets.
02992                                                          HW forces the SKIP to zero for packets on DPI
02993                                                          ports (32-35) when a PKT_INST_HDR is present.
02994                                                          See PIP_PRT_CFGB[ALT_SKP*] and PIP_ALT_SKIP_CFG.
02995                                                          See HRM sections "Parse Mode and Skip Length
02996                                                          Selection" and "Legal Skip Values"
02997                                                          for further details.
02998                                                          In DSA mode, indicates the DSA header length, not
02999                                                            Skip I size. (Must be 4,8,or 12)
03000                                                          In HIGIG mode, indicates both the Skip I size and
03001                                                            the HiGig header size (Must be 12 or 16).
03002                                                          If PTP_MODE, the 8B timestamp is prepended to the
03003                                                           packet.  SKIP should be increased by 8 to
03004                                                           compensate for the additional timestamp field. */
03005 #else
03006     uint64_t skip                         : 7;
03007     uint64_t reserved_7_7                 : 1;
03008     cvmx_pip_port_parse_mode_t mode       : 2;
03009     uint64_t dsa_en                       : 1;
03010     uint64_t higig_en                     : 1;
03011     uint64_t crc_en                       : 1;
03012     uint64_t reserved_13_15               : 3;
03013     uint64_t qos_vlan                     : 1;
03014     uint64_t qos_diff                     : 1;
03015     uint64_t qos_vod                      : 1;
03016     uint64_t qos_vsel                     : 1;
03017     uint64_t qos_wat                      : 4;
03018     uint64_t qos                          : 3;
03019     uint64_t hg_qos                       : 1;
03020     uint64_t grp_wat                      : 4;
03021     uint64_t inst_hdr                     : 1;
03022     uint64_t dyn_rs                       : 1;
03023     uint64_t tag_inc                      : 2;
03024     uint64_t rawdrp                       : 1;
03025     uint64_t reserved_37_39               : 3;
03026     uint64_t qos_wat_47                   : 4;
03027     uint64_t grp_wat_47                   : 4;
03028     uint64_t minerr_en                    : 1;
03029     uint64_t maxerr_en                    : 1;
03030     uint64_t lenerr_en                    : 1;
03031     uint64_t vlan_len                     : 1;
03032     uint64_t pad_len                      : 1;
03033     uint64_t len_chk_sel                  : 1;
03034     uint64_t ih_pri                       : 1;
03035     uint64_t reserved_55_63               : 9;
03036 #endif
03037     } s;

03308                                                           total SKIP (Skip I + header + Skip II
03309                                                             must be zero

03313                                                          0 = no packet inspection (Uninterpreted)

03315                                                          2 = IP parsing / skip to L3

03317                                                          Must be 2 ("skip to L2") when in DSA mode. */

03325                                                            the HiGig header size (Must be 12 or 16). */

03740 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
03741     uint64_t reserved_54_63               : 10;
03742     uint64_t portadd_en                   : 1;  /**< Enables PIP to optionally increment the incoming
03743                                                          port from the MACs based on port-kind
03744                                                          configuration and packet contents. */
03745     uint64_t inc_hwchk                    : 1;  /**< Include the HW_checksum into WORD0 of the WQE
03746                                                          instead of the L4PTR.  This mode will be
03747                                                          deprecated in future products. */
03748     uint64_t reserved_50_51               : 2;
03749     uint64_t grptagbase_msb               : 2;  /**< Most significant 2 bits of the GRPTAGBASE value. */
03750     uint64_t reserved_46_47               : 2;
03751     uint64_t grptagmask_msb               : 2;  /**< Most significant 2 bits of the GRPTAGMASK value.
03752                                                          group when GRPTAG is set. */
03753     uint64_t reserved_42_43               : 2;
03754     uint64_t grp_msb                      : 2;  /**< Most significant 2 bits of the 6-bit value
03755                                                          indicating the group to schedule to. */
03756     uint64_t grptagbase                   : 4;  /**< Offset to use when computing group from tag bits
03757                                                          when GRPTAG is set. */
03758     uint64_t grptagmask                   : 4;  /**< Which bits of the tag to exclude when computing
03759                                                          group when GRPTAG is set. */
03760     uint64_t grptag                       : 1;  /**< When set, use the lower bit of the tag to compute
03761                                                          the group in the work queue entry
03762                                                          GRP = WQE[TAG[3:0]] & ~GRPTAGMASK + GRPTAGBASE */
03763     uint64_t grptag_mskip                 : 1;  /**< When set, GRPTAG will be used regardless if the
03764                                                          packet IS_IP. */
03765     uint64_t tag_mode                     : 2;  /**< Which tag algorithm to use
03766                                                          0 = always use tuple tag algorithm
03767                                                          1 = always use mask tag algorithm
03768                                                          2 = if packet is IP, use tuple else use mask
03769                                                          3 = tuple XOR mask */
03770     uint64_t inc_vs                       : 2;  /**< determines the DSA/VLAN ID (VID) to be included in
03771                                                          tuple tag when VLAN stacking is detected
03772                                                          0 = do not include VID in tuple tag generation
03773                                                          1 = include VID (VLAN0) in hash
03774                                                          2 = include VID (VLAN1) in hash
03775                                                          3 = include VID ([VLAN0,VLAN1]) in hash */
03776     uint64_t inc_vlan                     : 1;  /**< when set, the DSA/VLAN ID is included in tuple tag
03777                                                          when VLAN stacking is not detected
03778                                                          0 = do not include VID in tuple tag generation
03779                                                          1 = include VID in hash */
03780     uint64_t inc_prt_flag                 : 1;  /**< sets whether the port is included in tuple tag */
03781     uint64_t ip6_dprt_flag                : 1;  /**< sets whether the TCP/UDP dst port is
03782                                                          included in tuple tag for IPv6 packets */
03783     uint64_t ip4_dprt_flag                : 1;  /**< sets whether the TCP/UDP dst port is
03784                                                          included in tuple tag for IPv4 */
03785     uint64_t ip6_sprt_flag                : 1;  /**< sets whether the TCP/UDP src port is
03786                                                          included in tuple tag for IPv6 packets */
03787     uint64_t ip4_sprt_flag                : 1;  /**< sets whether the TCP/UDP src port is
03788                                                          included in tuple tag for IPv4 */
03789     uint64_t ip6_nxth_flag                : 1;  /**< sets whether ipv6 includes next header in tuple
03790                                                          tag hash */
03791     uint64_t ip4_pctl_flag                : 1;  /**< sets whether ipv4 includes protocol in tuple
03792                                                          tag hash */
03793     uint64_t ip6_dst_flag                 : 1;  /**< sets whether ipv6 includes dst address in tuple
03794                                                          tag hash */
03795     uint64_t ip4_dst_flag                 : 1;  /**< sets whether ipv4 includes dst address in tuple
03796                                                          tag hash */
03797     uint64_t ip6_src_flag                 : 1;  /**< sets whether ipv6 includes src address in tuple
03798                                                          tag hash */
03799     uint64_t ip4_src_flag                 : 1;  /**< sets whether ipv4 includes src address in tuple
03800                                                          tag hash */
03801     cvmx_pow_tag_type_t tcp6_tag_type     : 2;  /**< sets the tag_type of a TCP packet (IPv6)
03802                                                          0 = ordered tags
03803                                                          1 = atomic tags
03804                                                          2 = Null tags */
03805     cvmx_pow_tag_type_t tcp4_tag_type     : 2;  /**< sets the tag_type of a TCP packet (IPv4)
03806                                                          0 = ordered tags
03807                                                          1 = atomic tags
03808                                                          2 = Null tags */
03809     cvmx_pow_tag_type_t ip6_tag_type      : 2;  /**< sets whether IPv6 packet tag type
03810                                                          0 = ordered tags
03811                                                          1 = atomic tags
03812                                                          2 = Null tags */

03814                                                          0 = ordered tags
03815                                                          1 = atomic tags

03818                                                          0 = ordered tags
03819                                                          1 = atomic tags
03820                                                          2 = Null tags */
03821     uint64_t grp                          : 4;  /**< 4-bit value indicating the group to schedule to */
03822 #else

04110 /**
04111  * cvmx_pip_qos_vlan#
04112  *
04113  * If the PIP indentifies a packet is DSA/VLAN tagged, then the QOS
04114  * can be set based on the DSA/VLAN user priority.  These eight register
04115  * comprise the QOS values for all DSA/VLAN user priority values.
04116  */
04117 union cvmx_pip_qos_vlanx {
04118     uint64_t u64;
04119     struct cvmx_pip_qos_vlanx_s {
04120 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04121     uint64_t reserved_7_63                : 57;
04122     uint64_t qos1                         : 3;  /**< DSA/VLAN QOS level
04123                                                          Selected when PIP_PRT_CFGx[QOS_VSEL] = 1 */
04124     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
04125     uint64_t qos                          : 3;  /**< DSA/VLAN QOS level
04126                                                          Selected when PIP_PRT_CFGx[QOS_VSEL] = 0 */
04127 #else
04128     uint64_t qos                          : 3;
04129     uint64_t reserved_3_3                 : 1;
04130     uint64_t qos1                         : 3;
04131     uint64_t reserved_7_63                : 57;
04132 #endif
04133     } s;
04134     struct cvmx_pip_qos_vlanx_cn30xx {
04135 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04136     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
04137     uint64_t qos                          : 3;  /**< VLAN QOS level */
04138 #else
04139     uint64_t qos                          : 3;
04140     uint64_t reserved_3_63                : 61;
04141 #endif
04142     } cn30xx;

04410 
04411 /**
04412  * cvmx_pip_stat0_#
04413  *
04414  * PIP Statistics Counters
04415  *
04416  * Note: special stat counter behavior
04417  *
04418  * 1) Read and write operations must arbitrate for the statistics resources
04419  *     along with the packet engines which are incrementing the counters.
04420  *     In order to not drop packet information, the packet HW is always a
04421  *     higher priority and the CSR requests will only be satisified when
04422  *     there are idle cycles.  This can potentially cause long delays if the
04423  *     system becomes full.
04424  *
04425  * 2) stat counters can be cleared in two ways.  If PIP_STAT_CTL[RDCLR] is
04426  *     set, then all read accesses will clear the register.  In addition,
04427  *     any write to a stats register will also reset the register to zero.
04428  *     Please note that the clearing operations must obey rule \#1 above.
04429  *
04430  * 3) all counters are wrapping - software must ensure they are read periodically
04431  *
04432  * 4) The counters accumulate statistics for packets that are sent to PKI.  If
04433  *    PTP_MODE is enabled, the 8B timestamp is prepended to the packet.  This
04434  *    additional 8B of data is captured in the octet counts.
04435  *
04436  * 5) X represents either the packet's port-kind or backpressure ID as
04437  *    determined by PIP_STAT_CTL[MODE]
04438  * PIP_STAT0_X = PIP_STAT_DRP_PKTS / PIP_STAT_DRP_OCTS
04439  */
04440 union cvmx_pip_stat0_x {
04441     uint64_t u64;
04442     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_x_s {
04443 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
04444     uint64_t drp_pkts                     : 32; /**< Inbound packets marked to be dropped by the IPD
04445                                                          QOS widget per port */
04446     uint64_t drp_octs                     : 32; /**< Inbound octets marked to be dropped by the IPD
04447                                                          QOS widget per port */
04448 #else
04449     uint64_t drp_octs                     : 32;
04450     uint64_t drp_pkts                     : 32;
04451 #endif
04452     } s;
04453     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_x_s             cn68xx;
04454     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_x_s             cn68xxp1;
04455 };
04456 typedef union cvmx_pip_stat0_x cvmx_pip_stat0_x_t;
04457 
04458 /**
04459  * cvmx_pip_stat0_prt#
04460  *
04461  * "PIP Statistics Counters
04462  * Note: special stat counter behavior
04463  * 1) Read and write operations must arbitrate for the statistics resources
04464  * along with the packet engines which are incrementing the counters.
04465  * In order to not drop packet information, the packet HW is always a
04466  * higher priority and the CSR requests will only be satisified when
04467  * there are idle cycles.  This can potentially cause long delays if the
04468  * system becomes full.
04469  * 2) stat counters can be cleared in two ways.  If PIP_STAT_CTL[RDCLR] is
04470  * set, then all read accesses will clear the register.  In addition,
04471  * any write to a stats register will also reset the register to zero.
04472  * Please note that the clearing operations must obey rule \#1 above.
04473  * 3) all counters are wrapping - software must ensure they are read periodically
04474  * 4) The counters accumulate statistics for packets that are sent to PKI.  If
04475  * PTP_MODE is enabled, the 8B timestamp is prepended to the packet.  This
04476  * additional 8B of data is captured in the octet counts.
04477  * PIP_STAT0_PRT = PIP_STAT_DRP_PKTS / PIP_STAT_DRP_OCTS"
04478  */
04479 union cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx {

04482 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD

04484                                                          QOS widget per port */
04485     uint64_t drp_octs                     : 32; /**< Inbound octets marked to be dropped by the IPD
04486                                                          QOS widget per port */
04487 #else
04488     uint64_t drp_octs                     : 32;
04489     uint64_t drp_pkts                     : 32;
04490 #endif
04491     } s;
04492     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn30xx;
04493     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn31xx;
04494     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn38xx;
04495     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn38xxp2;
04496     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn50xx;
04497     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn52xx;
04498     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn52xxp1;
04499     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn56xx;
04500     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn56xxp1;
04501     struct cvmx_pip_stat0_prtx_s          cn58xx;

04600     uint64_t bcast                        : 32; /**< Number of packets with L3 Broadcast Dest Address
04601                                                          that were dropped due to RED.
04602                                                          The HW considers an IPv4 packet to be broadcast
04603                                                          when all bits are set in the MSB of the
04604                                                          destination address. IPv6 does not have the
04605                                                          concept of a broadcast packets.
04606                                                          Only applies when the parse mode for the packet
04607                                                          is SKIP-TO-L2 and the packet is IP or the parse
04608                                                          mode for the packet is SKIP-TO-IP. */
04609     uint64_t mcast                        : 32; /**< Number of packets with L3 Multicast Dest Address
04610                                                          that were dropped due to RED.
04611                                                          The HW considers an IPv4 packet to be multicast
04612                                                          when the most-significant nibble of the 32-bit
04613                                                          destination address is 0xE (i.e. it is a class D
04614                                                          address). The HW considers an IPv6 packet to be
04615                                                          multicast when the most-significant byte of the
04616                                                          128-bit destination address is all 1's.
04617                                                          Only applies when the parse mode for the packet
04618                                                          is SKIP-TO-L2 and the packet is IP or the parse
04619                                                          mode for the packet is SKIP-TO-IP. */
04620 #else
04621     uint64_t mcast                        : 32;
04622     uint64_t bcast                        : 32;
04623 #endif
04624     } s;
04625     struct cvmx_pip_stat11_x_s            cn68xx;
04626     struct cvmx_pip_stat11_x_s            cn68xxp1;

05246 /**
05247  * cvmx_pip_stat_ctl
05248  *
05249  * Controls how the PIP statistics counters are handled.
05250  *
05251  */
05252 union cvmx_pip_stat_ctl {
05253     uint64_t u64;
05254     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_s {
05255 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05256     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
05257     uint64_t mode                         : 1;  /**< The PIP_STAT*_X registers can be indexed either by
05258                                                          port-kind or backpressure ID.
05259                                                          Does not apply to the PIP_STAT_INB* registers.
05260                                                          0 = X represents the packet's port-kind
05261                                                          1 = X represents the packet's backpressure ID */
05262     uint64_t reserved_1_7                 : 7;
05263     uint64_t rdclr                        : 1;  /**< Stat registers are read and clear
05264                                                          0 = stat registers hold value when read
05265                                                          1 = stat registers are cleared when read */
05266 #else
05267     uint64_t rdclr                        : 1;
05268     uint64_t reserved_1_7                 : 7;
05269     uint64_t mode                         : 1;
05270     uint64_t reserved_9_63                : 55;
05271 #endif
05272     } s;
05273     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx {
05274 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05275     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
05276     uint64_t rdclr                        : 1;  /**< Stat registers are read and clear
05277                                                          0 = stat registers hold value when read
05278                                                          1 = stat registers are cleared when read */
05279 #else
05280     uint64_t rdclr                        : 1;
05281     uint64_t reserved_1_63                : 63;
05282 #endif
05283     } cn30xx;
05284     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn31xx;
05285     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn38xx;
05286     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn38xxp2;
05287     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn50xx;
05288     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn52xx;
05289     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn52xxp1;
05290     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn56xx;
05291     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn56xxp1;
05292     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn58xx;
05293     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn58xxp1;
05294     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn61xx;
05295     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn63xx;
05296     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn63xxp1;
05297     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn66xx;
05298     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_s            cn68xx;
05299     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_s            cn68xxp1;
05300     struct cvmx_pip_stat_ctl_cn30xx       cn70xx;

05537 /**
05538  * cvmx_pip_tag_inc#
05539  *
05540  * # $PIP_TAG_INCX = 0x300+X X=(0..63) RegType=(RSL) RtlReg=(pip_tag_inc_csr_direct_TestbuilderTask)
05541  *
05542  */
05543 union cvmx_pip_tag_incx {
05544     uint64_t u64;
05545     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s {
05546 #ifdef __BIG_ENDIAN_BITFIELD
05547     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
05548     uint64_t en                           : 8;  /**< Which bytes to include in mask tag algorithm
05549                                                          Broken into 4, 16-entry masks to cover 128B
05550                                                          PIP_PRT_CFG[TAG_INC] selects 1 of 4 to use
05551                                                          registers  0-15 map to PIP_PRT_CFG[TAG_INC] == 0
05552                                                          registers 16-31 map to PIP_PRT_CFG[TAG_INC] == 1
05553                                                          registers 32-47 map to PIP_PRT_CFG[TAG_INC] == 2
05554                                                          registers 48-63 map to PIP_PRT_CFG[TAG_INC] == 3
05555                                                          [7] coresponds to the MSB of the 8B word
05556                                                          [0] coresponds to the LSB of the 8B word
05557                                                          If PTP_MODE, the 8B timestamp is prepended to the
05558                                                           packet.  The EN byte masks should be adjusted to
05559                                                           compensate for the additional timestamp field. */
05560 #else
05561     uint64_t en                           : 8;
05562     uint64_t reserved_8_63                : 56;
05563 #endif
05564     } s;
05565     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn30xx;
05566     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn31xx;
05567     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn38xx;
05568     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn38xxp2;
05569     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn50xx;
05570     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn52xx;
05571     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn52xxp1;
05572     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn56xx;
05573     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn56xxp1;
05574     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn58xx;
05575     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn58xxp1;
05576     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn61xx;
05577     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn63xx;
05578     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn63xxp1;
05579     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn66xx;
05580     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn68xx;
05581     struct cvmx_pip_tag_incx_s            cn68xxp1;

05816     uint64_t bcast                        : 32; /**< Number of packets with L3 Broadcast Dest Address
05817                                                          that were dropped due to RED.
05818                                                          The HW considers an IPv4 packet to be broadcast
05819                                                          when all bits are set in the MSB of the
05820                                                          destination address. IPv6 does not have the
05821                                                          concept of a broadcast packets.
05822                                                          Only applies when the parse mode for the packet
05823                                                          is SKIP-TO-L2 and the packet is IP or the parse
05824                                                          mode for the packet is SKIP-TO-IP. */
05825     uint64_t mcast                        : 32; /**< Number of packets with L3 Multicast Dest Address
05826                                                          that were dropped due to RED.
05827                                                          The HW considers an IPv4 packet to be multicast
05828                                                          when the most-significant nibble of the 32-bit
05829                                                          destination address is 0xE (i.e. it is a class D
05830                                                          address). The HW considers an IPv6 packet to be
05831                                                          multicast when the most-significant byte of the
05832                                                          128-bit destination address is all 1's.
05833                                                          Only applies when the parse mode for the packet
05834                                                          is SKIP-TO-L2 and the packet is IP or the parse
05835                                                          mode for the packet is SKIP-TO-IP. */
05836 #else

05839 #endif
